<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-07-03T16:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-07-03T16:30:00-05:00" n="684" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d684">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">819.796/17: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Venezuela</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Engert</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Caracas</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-07-03T17:00:00-04:30"><hi rend="italic">July 3,
                                            1928—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 10:16
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>71. My telegram No. 70, July 3, 4 p.m. I have been given to
                                understand that the United States has been rather slow in entering
                                this field,<note n="17" xml:id="d684fn17">See telegram No. 23, July
                                    11, 7 p.m., to the Chargé in Venezuela, <ref target="#pg_787">p.
                                        787</ref>.</note> and that it cannot hope to keep out
                                foreign interests indefinitely.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>